Five years after, the Governing Council of the Pharmacists Council of Nigeria (PCN) has inaugurated an investigative panel and disciplinary tribunal. This, the Council said will help ensure discipline and adherence to the ethics of the profession in the country. The PCN has been without governing council for about five years, as the previous Council was dissolved in 2015 while the new Council was inaugurated last month. Addressing journalists after the inauguration which was done via zoom in Abuja, chairman of the Governing Council, Prof. Ahmed Tijjani Mora, said that the inauguration was in accordance with the pharmacists laws. According to him, “The panel will discipline erring pharmacists. It is like a court. Then when  the cases are so severe, they will now shift to disciplinary tribunal which I head. “The governing council was dissolved in 2015, and it was only inaugurated just few months ago. So you can see that there were about five years that there was no investigative panel. Now, with the council in place, I have inaugurated the panel, it is the first of all the committees because of its importance. Those that are bridging the code of conduct, ethics will be brought to book.” Prof. Mora also received the National  Executive Committee of the Pharmaceutical Products Marketers Association of Nigeria (APPMAN), who paid a courtesy visit on him at the PCN headquarters, in Abuja. 